The paper deals with social choice rules, which are typically studied in the area of computational social choice (cs.GT). The use of metric spaces and distortion-based analysis suggests a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS), while the study of communication complexity and tradeoffs between distortion and communication suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the use of information theory techniques to derive lower bounds on distortion suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT).
